I miss Michelle and Barack so much that it makes me tear up whenever I watch any clip that one or both of them is in. It's so odd how much has changed since they were in the White House and how much more dark and depressing things seem right now, not only in Washington but just everywhere; within people. It was only about two years ago that the Obamas left the White House, but it feels like we are living in a completely different time. It makes me want to curl up in the fetal position, honestly.   Barack and Michelle were really good people. They were people I felt like I could have over to my house to have dinner, talk, dance, and watch a movie with or something. There was just such a warm energy around them, especially Michelle. And with Barack in charge, I felt safe. It makes me so pissed off to think about how terribly they were treated; the nasty things that people said about Michelle. I can't imagine what that must have been like for her, and sometimes when I watch videos of her from right before November 2016, I sense a sadness in her and it infuriates and saddens me. She was one of the warmest and most humble First Ladies this country has ever seen, and she didn't deserve to have people treating her the way that they did for 8 years. And it's a complete joke that right now, the same Republicans who did everything they could to make Barack's life Hell for 8 years including blocking his Supreme Court nominee for no reason at all, are yelling and bitching about the way that Democrats are acting toward the awful person who we have running this country right now and his Supreme Court pick who has been accused of sexual assault.  I miss the Obamas so much. It really sucks to feel like something good has ended and something awful has begun. The only thing that has made me hopeful that we are maybe heading toward positive change is seeing people like Beto O'Rourke, Cynthia Nixon, Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, etc.; new, fairly young candidates who, when they speak, make me feel comfortable. They are refreshingly honest, open, and intelligent and when they talk, you can tell they aren't full of shit. They want to make this country a better place and they have good ideas for ways to get us there. They aren't beholden to lobbyists, they aren't corrupt, they aren't ignorant...they are exactly the kind of people that would make Washington, and then the country, a better place. If enough people like them are elected to Congress, I believe things will get better.

Yeah, the guy who famously hated leftists and imprisoned and murdered socialists and communists was actually a socialist himself. Who knew. If you morons actually spend some of your free time reading actual books, you might actually learn something. Hitler was not a socialist. No serious historian has ever considered Hitler a socialist. The fact that the word 'socialist' was part of his party's name is about as relevant as the fact that North Korea calls itself a democratic republic.  For people who might read this and who are interested in the topic: the first important point is that the definition of left-wing and right-wing depends on the context. Conservatism in America today and conservatism in early 20th century Germany are very different things. American conservatism is heavily influenced by libertarianism, that's the origin of the whole small-state idea and the strongly capitalist ideology among US conservatives. Outside of the US however, there were and are different types of conservatism. And historically, conservatives were usually defenders of a strong state. A good example would be someone like Bismarck, a well-known conservative hardliner who wanted an extremely strong state and who also was the first politician to introduce public health care and similar welfare programs. It would be utterly idiotic to call him a socialist because of that. He absolutely despised socialists and considered them a huge threat. Which is actually the main reason why he introduced welfare programs, he wanted to cut off public support from socialists.  Strong state conservatism was common in Germany, it still is. In the beginning of the 20th century, there even were conservative movements in Germany who were very critical of capitalism. This is confusing to American conservatives because they only know libertarian conservatism.  Now the Nazis did have a left-leaning wing early on in the 1920s (left-leaning compared to the core of the party, not actually left-wing). Some of the people on the left wing of the party were actually in favor of a light form of socialism. Hitler was not one of them. He fought against the left-wing in his party and pretty much eradicated them. For Hitler, the word socialism in the party name was just a way to gain the support of the workers. German workers in the 1920s overwhelmingly supported the social democrats and the communists, so it was a good idea to make them think that the Nazis were socialist too. It was  effective propaganda.  Just read some of Hitler's speeches. He hated socialists, communists and leftists almost as much as he hated the Jews. He thought leftism was a Jewish conspiracy to destroy the world. Locking up leftists was almost the first thing he did after coming to power. He didn't lock up conservatives and right-wingers, he invited them to join forces with him.  Economically, the Nazis were mostly capitalist. They criticized capitalism at times but that was mostly a part of their antisemitism (Jewish bankers and so on) and remember: right-wing criticism of capitalism was common at the time. Big businesses thrived under the Nazis. Think of huge companies like IG Farben, Mercedes, BMW, Siemens, whatever. They were offered extremely favorable conditions by the Nazis and they made enormous amounts of money. Privatization was at an all-time high during the Third Reich. The Nazis did get involved in the economy, but that was mostly to build their massive war machine. It wasn't a result of some sort of leftist economic ideology, they just wanted to prepare for war.   Basically: read a fucking history book before you spread nonsense on the internet. And stop listening to Republican propaganda.
